Violence is all about the people involved in the violence. That's the only reason we care about the violence at all. I want to see the romantic leads pinned down together. I want to know they're afraid, and don't just tell me they're afraid, I want to taste it. Dig through your memory for the most frightening situations you've been in. Describe those thoughts and feelings.

>More than a few hours a day
Not necessarily. I spend usually two or so hours a day writing, and that's not terribly uncommon for people who don't write professionally. Commitment is important, but it's more important to be consistent than it is to dump a shitload of time in on any given day.

>Drafting
Yes. Personally, I subscribe to Kurt Vonnegut's description. There are two ways to go about writing: either agonize over every single paragraph as you write it and make everything as perfect as possible on a sentence-by-sentence basis, or vomit all of the everything onto a page and go back and agonize over that. Personally, I belong to the former category. That said, I usually still do at least one full revision pass even after agonizing over every sentence. It's not a particularly long process, and goddamn is it worth doing.

<Retconned>

A little author's commentary on Kit:

She was always planned to be Bonnie; even way back when she was mentioned offhand in BW. Originally it was Bonnie that Connie saw from the Ferris wheel in Looneyville, but the introduction of Trip changed that. And, the biggest change...

Originally, Kit wasn't motivated by friendship with Connie; in fact, she was in love with the detective. Before I changed her character considerably, an endgame choice would've been to either let Kit get away... or let her bury her face in Connie's chest and turn herself in afterward. But, that was getting too "porno" plot for me, and I much prefer how Kit came out now: a woman who eventually grew to love her fake life more than her real one.
